"Chylek P., Lesins G.","Multidecadal variability of Atlantic hurricane activity: 1851-2007",2008,"Journal of Geophysical Research Atmospheres","113","22", D22106,"","",,,10.1029/2008JD010036,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-58849089593&partnerID=40&md5=9272bea8c652b93ccaa7c3661b7c7d70","Space and Remote Sensing Sciences, Los Alamos National Laboratory, MS B244, Los Alamos, NM 87544, United States; Department of Physics and Atmospheric Science, Dalhousie University, Halifax, NS B3H 3J5, Canada","Chylek, P., Space and Remote Sensing Sciences, Los Alamos National Laboratory, MS B244, Los Alamos, NM 87544, United States; Lesins, G., Department of Physics and Atmospheric Science, Dalhousie University, Halifax, NS B3H 3J5, Canada","An analysis of Atlantic hurricane data (HURDAT), using a hurricane activity index that integrates over hurricane numbers, durations, and strengths during the years 1851-2007, suggests a quasi-periodic behavior with a period around 60 years superimposed upon a linearly increasing background. The linearly increasing background is significantly reduced or removed when various corrections were applied for hurricane undercounting in the early portion of the record. The periodic-like behavior is persistent in uncorrected HURDAT data as well as in data corrected for possible missing storms. The record contains two complete cycles: 1860-1920 and 1920-1980. The 2004 and 2005 hurricane seasons were unusual in that two intense hurricane seasons occurred in consecutive years. The probability for this happening in any given year is estimated to be less then 1%. Comparing the last 28 years (1980-2007) with the preceding 28 years (1953-1980), we find a modest increase in the number of minor hurricanes (category 1 and 2); however, we find no increase in the number of major hurricanes (category 3-5). The hurricane activity index is found to be highly correlated with the Atlantic Multidecadal Mode (AMM). If there is an increase in hurricane activity connected to a greenhouse gas induced global warming, it is currently obscured by the 60 year quasi-periodic cycle. Copyright 2008 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Climate change; Correlation methods; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Hurricanes; Meteorological problems; Storms; decadal variation; hurricane; marine atmosphere; probability; Atlantic Ocean",,,,,,"Bell, G., Chelliah, M., Leading tropical modes associated with interannual and multidecadal fluctuations in North Atlantic hurricane activity (2006) J. Clim, 19, pp. 590-612; Bell, G. D., M. S. Halpert, R. C. Shnell, R. W. Higgins, J. Lawrimore, V. E. Kousky, R. Tinker, W. Thiaw, M. Chelliah, and A. Artusa (2000), Climate assessment for 1999, Bull. Am. Meteorol. Soc., 81, S1-S50Chang, E., Guo, Y., Is the number of North Atlantic tropical cyclones significantly underestimated prior to the availability of satellite observations? (2007) Geophys. Res. Lett, 34, pp. L14801. , doi:10.1029/2007GL030169; Chylek, P., Lohmann, U., Dubey, M., Mishchenko, M., Kahn, R., Ohmura, A., Limit on climate sensitivity derived from recent satellite and surface observations (2007) J. Geophys. Res, 112, pp. D24S04. , doi:10.1029/ 2007JD008437; Emanuel, K., An air-sea interaction theory for tropical cyclones. part I: Steady state maintenance (1986) J. Atmos. Sci, 43, pp. 585-604; Emanuel, K., Increasing destructiveness of tropical cyclones over the past 30 years (2005) Nature, 436, pp. 686-689; Evan, A.T., Ocean temperature forcing by aerosols across the Atlantic tropical cyclone development region (2008), Q05VO4, doi:10.1029/2007GC001774Goldenberg, S.B., Landsea, C.W., Mestas-Nunez, A.M., Gray, W.M., The recent increase in Atlantic hurricane activity: Causes and implications (2001) Science, 293, pp. 474-479; Gray, W.M., Global view of the origins of tropical disturbances and storms (1968) Mon. Weather Rev, 96, pp. 669-700; Holland, G., Misuse of landfalls as a proxy for Atlantic tropical cyclone activity (2007) Eos Trans